Subsidy Trap
Cambridge, Mass. – No policy pits good economics against good politics more directly than food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming the central challenge for three of the world’s most important new leaders: Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Joko Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
Sisi faces a reduction in subsidies that may be marginally better than expected.
In contrast, Modi confronts a situation worse than anticipated, potentially even jeopardizing the long-awaited WTO agreement.
