In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies have often sparked unrest and even overthrown governments.
But Sisi's government seems to be making progress on this front.
Bread subsidies have been cut by 13%.
Sisi has no choice.
Even after the subsidy cuts, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year is 10% of GDP (it would be 14% without the cuts).
But few expected that Sisi, who took office amid turbulent politics, would move much faster than Modi in India, which had achieved a comprehensive economic reform through a sweeping democratic majority.
In Indonesia, Joko Widodo, who began his tenure in October, inherited fuel subsidies that cost as much as $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government spending), a burden that the country could ill afford.
The previous president, Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, had already taken a brave first step a year earlier by increasing fuel prices.
Joko Widodo's advisers recommend cutting the remaining subsidies, and he has straightforwardly said he plans to implement this gradually over four years.
Economists strongly oppose commodity subsidies, arguing that agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with large numbers of consumers and producers on both sides.
In imperfect markets — not large private monopolies — governments are the culprit.
Critics of the invisible hand argue that self-regulating private markets can fail in a variety of ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the main justifications for government intervention.
The debate over food and fossil fuel subsidies is sharp because they are often justified under the banners of the environment or equity, when in fact they do little or nothing to achieve those goals and can even work against them.
Less than 20% of Egypt’s food subsidies go to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies enrich the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transit.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) subsidies went to the poorest 1%, while 52.6% went to the richest 5%.
Worldwide, less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies actually reach the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy, as evidenced by the Modi government, which sought to protect farm subsidies.
Indeed, the Modi government has thwarted the World Trade Organization negotiations, which were supposed to be the most significant advance in multilateral trade talks in over a decade.
Agri-subsidies sometimes enrich producers at the expense of consumers, especially in poor countries; and sometimes enrich consumers at the expense of producers, especially in rich countries.
India's policies aim to have it all.
The result is a feat: wheat is distributed to consumers at artificially depressed prices, while surpluses abound because farmers get paid above-market rates.
(Farmers also receive subsidies in the form of electricity, water, and fertilizer, which contribute to environmental degradation.
) The government acquires vast quantities of corrupt rice and wheat, while a small portion of the distribution is both corrupt and fails to help the poor.
Government might continue with subsidies and storage.
But it knows this would violate WTO rules.
Since these rules cannot be changed permanently, Modi vetoed the WTO's eagerly awaited Trade Facilitation Agreement.
Once subsidies are implemented, they are hard to reverse.
When world prices rise (as they did in the last decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot shield them from the shock.
But people accustomed to official food and energy prices will demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a strong argument that subsidies should not have been implemented in the first place.
That does not mean, however, that maintaining subsidies will always be the shrewd politician's best choice once they are in place.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents could erupt.
Similarly, if growing inequality eventually leads to higher retail prices, dithering leaders will not benefit either.
In an ideal scenario, reducing food and energy subsidies should be accompanied by other more efficient pro-poor support measures.
Developing countries have already learned much about effective transfer mechanisms, such as conditional cash transfer innovations like Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades and Brazil's Bolsa Família, as well as technological innovations like India's Unique Identification system.
But some countries may find themselves forced to adjust budgets during crises, leaving them with no money available for transfers to cushion the pain.
Savvy politicians might consider implementing unpopular adjustments early on in their tenures.
Both Joko Widodo and Sisi have followed this approach.
And Modi, who won elections on a platform of market reforms, has lagged behind.
